\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # introduction}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Introducing Nonograms}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Introducing Nonograms;What is a Nonogram?;Nonograms}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Introducing Nonograms\par\plain\f8\fs20
\par
\plain \ul\f8\fs20 Nonogram's\plain \ul\v\f8\fs20 typnono\plain \f8\fs20  belong to the grid family of puzzle's and are composed of a grid of squares, which can either be fully filled with one colour or left blank. (The Nonogram Solver for Windows uses grey to represent the unfilled squares and white to represent the filled squares.) Basic numerical data about the arrangement of the filled and unfilled squares is given, and it is up to the user to fill in the squares.\par
\par
The Nonogram Solver uses a variety of algorithmns to obtain a solution all of which can be tailored by the user. How to do so is given in the \plain \uldb\f8\fs20 Display Options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 display\plain \f8\fs20  and the \plain \uldb\f8\fs20 Solution Options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain \f8\fs20  help entries.\par
\par
In order to perform a conversion, the program must be given an appropriate data file - see \plain \uldb\f8\fs20 Data 
Files\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 datafiles\plain \f8\fs20  for more information.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # datafiles}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Data files}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Data files;Data format}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Data files\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
Data files must be in a plain ASCII format (such as those produced using NOTEPAD etc)\par
\par
The format is of one title line, followed by the puzzle data. The puzzle will be in the form of a 20x25 
grid and the data for the side of 20 must be entered first, followed by that for the side of 25. Each 
line of data must be terminated by a '99'.\par
\par
For example:\par
\par \f1\fs18
White Rabbit Nonogram\tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Title line\par \f1\fs18
1 2 10 2 99 \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - First line of data out of block of twenty\par \f1\fs18
2 3 2 4 99\tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Second line of data out of block of twenty\par \f1\fs18
3 4 1 6 99\tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Third line of data out of block of twenty\par \f1\fs18
: : : :  : \tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Another 41 rows of data\par \f1\fs18
4 5 3 11 99 \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - 25th line of data out of block of twenty five\par \f1\fs18
[EOF]\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - End of file marker\par
\par
NOTE: The end of file marker, [EOF], should not be manually entered in the file as it will be 
inserted by the editor.\par
\par
Also please note that all Nonogram data files should be saved with the 
extension '.NGM'. Although the DOS version of the Nonogram Solver will only recognise data files with this extension, the Windows version can read in other data files.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # solution}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Solution options}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Solution options;VARS}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Solution options\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
Various solution options are available. Choose Options|Solutions to access the options dialog box. By toggling the status of the check boxes it is possible to enable/disable various solution options - it is also possible to alter the size of the \plain \uldb\f8\fs20 VARS\uldb\v\f8\fs20 vars \plain\f8\fs20  array.\par
\par
\plain \b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\par
