\plain \b\f8\fs24 A typical Nonogram\par\plain \f8\fs20
\par
{\f2\cf2 \{bml nonogram.bmp\}}This is a typical solved Nonogram, as produced by the Nonogram Solver program. It is 'Scottie'.
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # quickstart}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Quick start}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Quick start;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Quick start\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
This algorithm, as suggested by the name speeds up the rate at which the solution initially progresses. It essentially looks for 'safe bets' in the data (eg rows which can only be arranged in one way) and fills them in.\par
\par
It should be noted that this algorthim, if enabled, is only used once at the start of a solution run.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Solution options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # edgecheck}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Edge checking}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Edge checking;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Edge checking\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
This algorithm is designed to accelerate the starting speed of the solution. This time only the outer rim of the puzzle is scanned. If a fully filled square is found in any of these positions it is extended by the amount given in the puzzle data set. \par
\par
In general this algorithm does not significantly decrease the time taken to find a solution.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Solution options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # fullrow}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Full row testing}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Full row testing;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Full row testing\par\plain \f8\fs20
\par
This checks for full rows and if it finds one marks it as such, so that no other algorithm tries to check it in future. It can speed up the solution time noticeably, particularly if used with the combinational algorithm.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Solution options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # rowfoll}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Row following}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Row following;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Row following\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
This method starts at the beginning of a row or column and tries to work across to the other end, using the puzzle data. Can be useful depending on the puzzle.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Solution options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # combin}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ Combinational algorithm}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K Combinational algorithm;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  Combinational algorithm\par\plain \f8\fs20
\par
This is the most important algorithm. Basically it calculates the number of ways in which the available data can be arranged into any particular row or column. It discounts any solutions which disagree with the data already present and temporarily stores any solutions which appear to fit. It then examines all these solutions looking for matching data, before updating the grid with any new data it has found.\par
\par
How many potential solutions it can store before giving up (it will give up and move to the next line if it finds more potential solutions than it can store) depends on the setting of \plain \uldb\f8\fs20 
VARS\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 vars\plain \f8\fs20 . The default value is 20, but this can be raised to four hundred. Obviously this will increase the computational time, and a value greater than twenty is usually only required if the combinational algorithm is being used on its own.\par
\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Also See\par
\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Contents\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 main_contents\plain \uldb\f8\fs20 \par
Solution options\plain \uldb\v\f8\fs20 solution\plain 
\par \pard\page 
\pard \qj\sl0 {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 # vars}${\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 $ VARS}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s1240 \fs20 K VARS;Solution options}}
\plain \b\f8\fs24  VARS\par \plain \f8\fs20
\par
This array is used in conjunction with the combinational algorithm and has a default value of twenty. In most cases this should be sufficient to solve virtually all the supplied test Nonograms. Only one, NARCISSU.NGM, requires this value to be increased for a solution to be found. A value of two hundred easily solves this Nonogram.\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Typical solution times using v1.1a\par
\par
\plain \i\f8\fs20
\par
\tab VARS \tab  Time  \tab  Successful\par
\par \plain \f8\fs20
\tab 5 \tab  0.3 \tab NO\par
\tab 10 \tab 15.8 \tab YES\par
\tab 20 \tab 12.7 \tab YES\par
\tab 50 \tab 13.9 \tab YES\par
\tab 100 \tab 14.2 \tab YES\par
\par
\b\f8\fs20 Typical solution times using v1.2\par
\par
\plain \i\f8\fs20
\par
\tab VARS \tab  Time  \tab  Successful\par
\par \plain \f8\fs20
\tab 5 \tab  0.2 \tab NO\par
\tab 10 \tab 11.3 \tab YES\par
\tab 20 \tab 9.2 \tab YES\par
\tab 50 \tab 10.0 \tab YES\par
\tab 100 \tab 10.2 \tab YES\par
\par
NOTE: These results were obtained using GEMINI.NGM on a 486SX25 PC.
\par
\par
It should also be borne in mind that the best solution time obtained using v1.2 to solve GEMINI.NGM was 4.4 seconds. This was obtained by setting the VARS size to 20 and turning edge checking and row following off. On a 386SX25 this time increased to 10.98 seconds.
\par
\par
